circumstances.circumstancesOfDisappearance: Reamer was initially reported missing on April 4, 1994, but last had contact on March 28, 1994.  Reamer's girlfriend from Three Forks, MT dropped him off at his apartment on Wilder Ave. in Helena, MT on March 27, 1994. He had spent the weekend with her and their young son. She claimed there was an unknown male at his apartment when she dropped him off. The next morning the girlfriend and "surrogate" mother both claimed to have spoken to Reamer on the phone before he left for class at Carroll College. The neighbor remembered seeing him on the night of the 27th, but he didn't come over for breakfast the morning of the 28th as planned.  Personal belongings, including his wallet, bicycle and school books, were left behind, and his vehicle remained parked outside the apartment.  His favorite cowboy hat was missing.

physicalFeatureDescriptions.description: Tattoo on upper right arm with the words "Makah Nation" encompassing a circular design surrounded by serpents and two feathers hanging down. The tattoo had a lot of yellow, red, and green in it. That design is the memorial design "Anataquis" for John's great grandmother, made by her grandson.

images.caption: Reamer with tattoo on right arm

In 2001, before he could be extradited back to Montana for the trial, he killed himself in prison.

circumstances.circumstancesOfDisappearance: Curtis Holmen was last seen at his home on Washburn Avenue on the evening of July 22, 1984 when he went to drive on the highway to charge his truck’s battery. The truck he was driving was found 12 days later on a back road near Placid Lake in Missoula County. His wallet was found inside and the truck appeared to be in good condition with no sign of foul play.  Extensive searches were conducted in the area where the truck was found but he was never located.   His disappearance is believed to be due to an accident in the woods or possibly an attack by an animal.

Tom was employed for the summer with the National Forestry Service at the forest ranger station near Troy, MT.  Tom and a couple friends from the station were floating down the Kootenai River in innertubes between Troy and Libby.  They hit rough water and Tom was flipped out of his innertube.  The others were unable to reach him.  They saw him come to the surface twice and then disappear.  Searches of the area were unable to locate him.

circumstances.circumstancesOfDisappearance: Frey, an experienced hunter and woodsman, left his home in Missoula to hunt up Deep Creek and never returned.  It snowed on the day he left home and the following day.  Friends, family and law enforcement searched extensively, but remains were never found.  Frey may have walked into any of several other drainages in the area including Petty Creek.
